        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">When light is flashed onto one eye, both the eyes&rsquo; pupils constrict as a response. This is known as the pupillary light reflex. Where is the center for this reflex located?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2229030",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31447,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Midbrain </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>pupillary reflex fibres</strong> are relayed to the <strong>PRETECTAL NUCLEUS</strong> located in the <strong>midbrain</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Afferent: <strong>Optic Nerve</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Efferent: <strong>Short ciliary nerves</strong> </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/12/13/picture7.jpg\" style=\"height:485px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Midbrain: The <strong>midbrain plays a crucial role in the control of eye movements</strong>, primarily through <strong>two key structures</strong>: the <strong>superior colliculi</strong> and the <strong>oculomotor nerve nuclei</strong> (cranial nerve III).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Superior Colliculi</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></span></span>\r\n\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:disc\">\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>superior colliculi</strong>, located in the <strong>tectum of the midbrain</strong>, are involved in the <strong>initiation of saccadic eye movements.</strong> These are <strong>rapid, jerky movements of the eyes</strong> that abruptly change the point of fixation.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">They <strong>receive visual inputs as well as inputs from other sensory modalities</strong> and are responsible for directing the eyes toward an object of interest, particularly in response to new or sudden visual stimuli.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Oculomotor Nerve Nuclei</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></span></span>\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:disc\">\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>oculomotor nerve nuclei</strong> control most of the <strong>eye&#39;s movements and are responsible for the constriction of the pupil</strong> and maintaining an open eyelid.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">They <strong>coordinate the actions of the muscles</strong> that control the <strong>movement of the eyeball and the upper eyelid.</strong> Specifically, they innervate the superior, inferior, and medial rectus muscles, the inferior oblique muscle, the levator palpebrae superioris, and the sphincter pupillae.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Additionally, the <strong>midbrain is involved in the integration of the vestibulo-ocular reflex</strong> (VOR), which stabilizes the visual field during head movements, and the accommodation reflex.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Pons</strong>: <strong>Pontine centres</strong> are involved in <strong>optokinetic nystagmus</strong>. Pontine lesions cause <strong>dolls eye movement.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D: Cerebellum</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">- Cerebellum is involved in <strong>integration and coordination of optokinetic nystagmus</strong>. Characteristics of cerebellar nystagmus include:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Direction</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: It is typically horizontal, but can also be vertical or rotary. The direction of the nystagmus may change depending on the direction of gaze.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Gaze-Evoked Nystagmus</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: This form of nystagmus becomes more pronounced when the patient looks to the side. It is due to the failure of the cerebellum to hold steady gaze, leading to a drift of the eyes back to the central position, followed by a corrective saccade.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Intensity and Amplitude</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: The intensity and amplitude of the nystagmus can increase with the degree of lateral gaze and decrease or disappear with gaze towards the midline.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Associated Symptoms</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Patients with cerebellar nystagmus may also exhibit other signs of cerebellar dysfunction, such as ataxia, dysarthria, and tremor.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understand that the <strong>pupillary light reflex</strong> is <strong>mediated by the midbrain</strong>, involving an interplay between the optic and oculomotor nerves.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><u>REF</u>:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">PARSON&rsquo;S DISEASES OF EYE PAGE 33</span></strong></span></span></p>",
