          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Wernicke’s pupil</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A patient undergoing perimetry has the following visual field defect. What is the pupillary abnormality expected in this case?</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/12/13/picture9_pHTRUUf.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"140\"></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2050184",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31449,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Wernicke’s pupil</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The picture shows <strong>right homonymous hemianopia</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Site of lesion – <strong>left optic tract</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This is associated with <strong>Wernicke’s pupil</strong>.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/12/15/screenshot-2023-12-15-113654.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1000\" height=\"144\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/12/13/picture10_9T5ZbW6.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"509\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Wernicke Pupil</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">When the <strong>optic chiasm is bisected sagittally</strong>, the <strong>nasal halves of each retina become insensitive to light</strong> so that <strong>there is not only a bitemporal hemianopia but also a bitemporal pupillary hemiakinesia</strong>; that is, light falling on the nasal retina of either eye will fail to produce a pupillary constriction. Thus, if a very bright but small beam of light such as that produced by a slit lamp is shined on the nonseeing hemiretina of a patient with damage to the optic chiasm or optic tract and then is shined on the seeing hemiretina, it is possible to see that the pupil reacts better when the light shines on the seeing hemiretina than when it shines on the nonseeing retina.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A</strong>. <strong>Argyll Robertson Pupil:</strong> This is a <strong>condition where pupils are small and irregular but do not constrict</strong> when <strong>exposed to bright light</strong> (light-near dissociation). They do, however, <strong>constrict with accommodation</strong>. It is classically associated with neurosyphilis, particularly tabes dorsalis, and does not have a direct correlation with homonymous hemianopia.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Adie’s Pupil:</strong> Also known as <strong>tonic pupil</strong>, it is usually <strong>unilateral and is larger than the other pupil</strong>. It reacts poorly to light but may have a better near response. This <strong>condition is caused by damage to the postganglionic fibers</strong> of the parasympathetic innervation of the eye and is not related to visual field defects.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Marcus Gunn Pupil:</strong> Also known as a <strong>relative afferent pupillary defect</strong> (RAPD), it is a <strong>sign of asymmetrical optic nerve dysfunction</strong>. It is <strong>detected using the swinging flashlight test</strong>. However, in homonymous hemianopia, the optic nerve function is typically preserved until the optic chiasm, so a Marcus Gunn pupil is not expected.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In a case of <strong>right homonymous hemianopia</strong>, the <strong>lesion lies at the level of left optic tract</strong>, and the <strong>pupillary abnormality</strong> seen in these cases will be <strong>Wernicke’s pupil</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>REF</u>: KHURANA COMPREHENSIVE OPHTHALMOLOGY 5<sup>TH</sup> EDITION pg.no: 312</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>2. Walsh and Hoyt’s Clinical Neuro-Ophthalmology 6<sup>th</sup> Edition pg. No: 747</strong></span></p>",
