        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. C) Marcus Gunn pupil</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This is a <strong>form of paradoxical response of a pupil to light</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Marcus Gunn pupil&nbsp;</strong>is characterized by a relative <strong>afferent pupillary defect</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Causes: Retinal disease, Optic nerve disease, Glaucoma, Trauma.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">It is detected via <strong>SWINGING FLASHLIGHT TEST</strong>.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/12/13/picture16_lAqjlNd.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"361\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Wernicke’s Pupil:</strong> if a very <strong>bright</strong> but <strong>small beam of light</strong> such as that produced by a slit lamp is <strong>shined on the nonseeing hemiretina of a patient</strong> with <strong>damage to the optic chiasm</strong> or <strong>optic tract</strong> and then is shined on the seeing hemiretina, it is possible to see that the pupil reacts better when the light shines on the seeing hemiretina than when it shines on the nonseeing retina.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B</strong>. <strong>Horner’s Pupil:</strong> This is a <strong>part of Horner's syndrome</strong>, which <strong>includes ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis on the affected side</strong>. The pupil in Horner's syndrome is smaller on the affected side but reacts normally to light and accommodation. This is not consistent with the described findings.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D</strong>. <strong>Adie’s Pupil:</strong> This involves a <strong>tonic pupil that is larger than the other and reacts poorly to light but may have a better near response</strong>. It's usually caused by damage to the postganglionic fibers of the parasympathetic innervation of the eye. This does not match the clinical picture of an RAPD.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In a <strong>patient presenting with a sudden decrease in vision in one eye</strong> and an <strong>observed pupil response where shining light in the unaffected eye causes both pupils to constrict</strong>, but shining it in the affected eye causes both to dilate, the likely diagnosis is a <strong>Marcus Gunn pupil</strong> (Relative Afferent Pupillary Defect), indicative of asymmetric optic nerve dysfunction.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>REF</u>: KHURANA COMPREHENSIVE OPHTHALMOLOGY 5<sup>TH</sup> EDITION pg.no: 312</strong></span></p>",
